Subsetting anndata objects

Author
Affiliation

Griffen Wakelin

Dalhousie University

February 6, 2024

Modified

February 6, 2024

Subsetting anndata objects is simple, given that there exists some metric or metadata upon which you would like to subset.

import scanpy as sc

adata = sc.read_h5ad("example.h5ad")
print(adata)
AnnData object with n_obs  n_vars = 6551  19755

For example, if we wanted to subset an anndata object based on clusters, we would first cluster the data:

sc.pp.pca(adata)
sc.pp.neighbors(adata)
sc.tl.leiden(adata)
sc.tl.umap(adata)
print(adata)
AnnData object with n_obs  n_vars = 6551  19755
    obs: 'leiden'
    uns: 'pca', 'neighbors', 'leiden', 'umap'
    obsm: 'X_pca', 'X_umap'
    varm: 'PCs'
    obsp: 'distances', 'connectivities'

Note that the clustering metadata is stored in the .obs slot, under the column name leiden (by default). We subset based on elements in the .obs dataframe most often.

adata.obs
leiden
AAACCCAAGCCTAACT-1 7
AAACCCACAAGCACCC-1 15
AAACCCAGTACCGTGC-1 5
AAACCCAGTTGGTACT-1 4
AAACGAAAGGCGCTCT-1 2
... ...
TTTGTTGGTTTGCCGG-1 2
TTTGTTGTCACACCCT-1 3
TTTGTTGTCGAATGCT-1 15
TTTGTTGTCGTCCATC-1 10
TTTGTTGTCTTACCAT-1 1

6551 rows 1 columns

We can select cluster(s) of interest and subset the anndata object accordingly. Since the clusters for each cell are stored in the .obs metadata slot, under the column name leiden, we would format our code to subset only cluster 1 as:

adata_cluster1 = adata[adata.obs['leiden'].isin(['1']), :]
print(adata_cluster1)
View of AnnData object with n_obs  n_vars = 731  19755
    obs: 'leiden'
    uns: 'pca', 'neighbors', 'leiden', 'umap'
    obsm: 'X_pca', 'X_umap'
    varm: 'PCs'
    obsp: 'distances', 'connectivities'

Similarly, we can subset multiple clusters into an object by providing them separated by commas:

adata_cluster1_cluster2_cluster6 = adata[adata.obs['leiden'].isin(['1','2','6']), :]
print(adata_cluster1_cluster2_cluster6)
View of AnnData object with n_obs  n_vars = 1689  19755
    obs: 'leiden'
    uns: 'pca', 'neighbors', 'leiden', 'umap'
    obsm: 'X_pca', 'X_umap'
    varm: 'PCs'
    obsp: 'distances', 'connectivities'

To visualize what each one of these subsetting operations did, we can plot all the UMAPs together.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

fig, ax = plt.subplots(3, 1, figsize=(6,16))
sc.pl.umap(adata, color=['leiden'], ax=ax[0], show=False, title='Original')
sc.pl.umap(adata_cluster1, color=['leiden'], ax=ax[1], show=False, title='Subset: Cluster 1')
sc.pl.umap(adata_cluster1_cluster2_cluster6, color=['leiden'], ax=ax[2], show=False, title='Subset: Clusters 1, 2, 6')
plt.show()
